{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>Type IV secretion systems are virulence determinants in many bacteria and share homology with many conjugal transfer systems. The VirB system of Agrobacterium tumefaciens, which delivers both virulence proteins and oncogenic T-DNA to plant hosts, is the best studied Type IV secretion system.</p>\n\n<p>This group contains the VirJ/AcvB component of Type IV secretion systems. A. tumefaciens VirJ and AcvB are Ti plasmid and chromosome-encoded, respectively [[cite:PUB00012242], [cite:PUB00014422], [cite:PUB00014402]], and are required for T-DNA transfer into plants [[cite:PUB00014385]]. It has been suggested that VirJ evolved from AcvB, presumably for a more specialised role in tumorigenesis [[cite:PUB00014385]].</p>\n\n<p>It is believed that AcvB binds to the T-strand in periplasm and mediates the transfer of the T-strand from A. tumefaciens to the host plant cell [[cite:PUB00014405]]. Similarly, export substrates are believed to associate with the virulence protein VirJ in the periplasm, and VirJ is believed to be involved in the second step of type IV secretion, i.e. movement of substrates from the periplasm to the plant cell [[cite:PUB00012242]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure nil, :overlaps-with nil, :member-databases {"pirsf" {"PIRSF029063" "Type IV secretory pathway, VirJ component"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Type IV secretory pathway, VirJ component", "short" "IV_sec_VirJ"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 0, "domain_architectures" 0, "proteomes" 411, "taxa" 2496, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 3150, "sets" 0, "proteins" 2676, "structural_models" {"alphafold" 2085}, "pathways" 0}, :integrated nil, :cross-references {}, :set-info nil, :accession "IPR011225", :literature {"PUB00012242" {"URL" nil, "issue" "5", "authors" ["Pantoja M" "Chen L" "Chen Y" "Nester EW."], "ISO_jour